        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our observations aim at obtaining high-fidelity continuum and CO line emission maps in Band 6. The integrated continuum flux is 32 mJy (as measured in our CARMA data), with an expected peak brightness of 9 mJy/beam at the ALMA resolution. In order to probe the radial and vertical extent of the disk, we need a high signal-to-noise ratio at the peak brightness. Specifically, to trace the dust emission at SNR&gt;3 up to 3 scale heights (i.e., if the large dust grains are not settled), we request a signal-to-noise of 200 at the peak brightness, i.e., an r.m.s. of 45 microJy/beam. This can be achieved in 19 min on source with the selected array configuration and 3.75 Ghz of continuum bandwidth.

The peak emission of the weakest CO line (C18O) is expected to be about 15 mJy/beam; the other lines are expected to be 2-3 times stronger. In order to be sensitive to faint emission at large distances from the star, we request a peak signal-to-noise of 15, or an r.m.s. of 1 mJy/beam, after integration over the entire line width (cloud contamination is not an issue for the rare isotopologues). Based on the sensitivity calculator, this can be achieved in 30 min integration on source, which in turn drives the total requested time for this science goal.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For the continuum observations, we use the maximum achievable bandwidth with two separate basebands (3.75 GHz). For the line observations, we selected a correlator set-up with 0.3 km/s sampling. We are primarily interested in total line emission to map the disk surface and interior, for which spectral resolution is not at a premium. However, while cloud contamination is not expected to be significant (the source is optically detected, having visual extinction Av&lt;3 mag, and is not superimposed on strong emission from the Taurus cloud), we anticipate that the 12CO emission could be contaminated within 1-1.5 km/s of the systemic velocity. With 1.5-2 km/s line width that is uncontaminated in both the blue and red wings of the line, we thus adopt an 0.3 km/s sampling, sufficient to probe the Keplerian rotation of the gaseous disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The total extent of the disk, as traced in scattered light images, is 6"; however the largest extent of the emission mapped with CARMA is 4" as surface brightness decreases sharply towards the disk's outer edge. Although we wish to achieve high spatial resolution, we need to avoid filtering out emission at low spatial frequencies. As a trade off, we have thus selected the C36-5 configuration, which yields a 0.29x0.44 arcsec beam for this Northern source. While the beam is significantly elongated, it will be so along the N-S direction. Because the disk is oriented almost along this direction (position angle of the midplane: -27 deg), we will still be able to use the full ALMA resolution to probe the vertical extent of the disk, while the resolution in the other direction is still a significant improvement over our previous CARMA observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
