        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our observations aim at obtaining high-fidelity continuum and CO line emission maps in Band 6. The integrated continuum flux, extrapolated from our measured 91 mJy flux density at 870 micron with SMA, is 41 mJy, with an expected peak brightness of 10 mJy/beam at the ALMA resolution. In order to probe the radial and vertical extent of the disk, we need a high signal-to-noise ratio at the peak brightness. Specifically, to trace the dust emission at SNR&gt;3 up to 3 scale heights (i.e., if the large dust grains are not settled), we request a signal-to-noise of 200 at the peak brightness, i.e., an r.m.s. of 50 microJy/beam. This can be achieved in 15 min on source with the selected array configuration and 3.75 Ghz of continuum bandwidth.

Based on the SMA detection of the 12CO 3-2 line, and using line ratios that are 1) typically observed in protoplanetary disks, and 2) predicted by our ProDiMO models (specifically, 20:1 between 12CO and C18O, and 2:1 between the 30-2 and 2.5-1 transitions), we expect the peak emission of the weakest CO line (C18O) to be about 15 mJy/beam; the other lines are expected to be 2-3 times stronger. In order to be sensitive to faint emission at large distances from the star, we request a peak signal-to-noise of 15, or an r.m.s. of 1 mJy/beam, after integration over the entire line width (cloud contamination is not an issue for the rare isotopologues). Based on the sensitivity calculator, this can be achieved in 25 min integration on source, thus driving the total requested time.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For the continuum observations, we use the maximum achievable bandwidth with two separate basebands (3.75 GHz). For the line observations, we selected a correlator set-up with 0.3 km/s sampling. We are primarily interested in total line emission to map the disk surface and interior, for which spectral resolution is not at a premium. However, while cloud contamination is not expected to be significant (the source is optically detected, having visual extinction Av &lt; 3mag, and is not superimposed on strong emission from the Ophiuchus cloud), we anticipate that the 12CO emission could be contaminated within 1-1.5 km/s of the systemic velocity. With 1.5-2 km/s line width that is uncontaminated in both the blue and red wings of the line, we thus adopt an 0.3 km/s sampling, sufficient to probe the Keplerian rotation of the gaseous disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The total extent of the disk, as traced in scattered light images, is 3". Although we wish to achieve high spatial resolution, we need to avoid filtering out significantly emission at low spatial frequencies. As a trade off, we have thus selected the C36-5 configuration, which yields a nearly round 0.29 arcsec beam. Thus, we will still be able to use the full ALMA resolution to probe both the vertical and radial extent of the disk, improving by a factor of 2-3 over the resolution of our previous SMA observations. This gain will prove critical to be able to separate the two disk surfaces , which are completely blended in the SMA observations (as seen in Fig. 2).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
